<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-158-464  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 158 464.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Jan 19 1989 v15 n2 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Eliminating the guesswork: laying down a few ground rules canreduce the risk of failure.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hall, Ted.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A recent survey indicates that 70 percent of all systemdevelopment and integration projects on the corporate level arefailures in terms of cost and scheduling.andP;  This surprising figureindicates that in many instances some basic precepts of long rangeplanning and management by objectives are not being followed.andP;  Toavoid getting stuck with an unrealistic cost or scheduling agenda,the planner needs to follow a few basic rules.andP;  The systemrequirements, including the possibility that an upgrade willsuffice, need to be addressed in detail.andP;  Alternative solutionsshould be developed.andP;  The estimation of development andoperational costs should be methodical.andP;  A formal cost-benefitanalysis report should be written.andP;  The end product should beclearly defined in terms of sub-products and deliverables.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EstimationProject ManagementComputer Systems IntegratorsGoals and ObjectivesMethodsManagement by Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>